re). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor Towne was born in 1426, in Throwley, Kent, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Thomas at Towne and Joane Cheyne. She married Richard Lewknor about 1460, in Postling, Kent, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1476, in Postling, Kent, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1426–1476":"1426–1476","1416–1446":"1416–1446","1428–Female":"1428–Surnud","1431–Female":"1431–Surnud","1433–1476":"1433–1476","1457–1522":"1457–1522","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1380–1430":"1380–1430","–Female":"Surnud","1460":"1460","1380":"1380","1426":"1426","1425":"1425","1457":"1457","1446":"1446","1522":"1522","1433":"1433","1476":"1476","1431":"1431","1430":"1430","about 1476":"umbes 1476","about 1430":"umbes 1430","about 1460":"umbes 1460","1428":"1428","1416":"1416","Throwley, Kent, England":"Throwley, Kent, England","Postling, Kent, England":"Postling, Kent, England","Postling, Shepway, Kent, England":"Postlin